results.name: Number of coprime pairs of divisors > 1 of n.
comment: Also the number of divisors of n^2 which do not divide n and which are less than n. See link for proof. - _Andrew Weimholt_, Dec 06 2009
a(3*2^n) = n; if x = 2^n, then a(x) = a(2*x); and if x is not a power of two, then a(x) = y then a(2*x) > y. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Dec 16 2009
a(n) = 0 iff n is a prime power. - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Aug 20 2013
link: Reinhard Zumkeller, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000
Andrew Weimholt, Proof of an alternative characterization
formula: a(n) = #{(x,y): 1 < x < y, x|n, y|n and gcd(x, y) = 1}.
a(n) = A018892(n) - A000005(n). - _Franklin T. Adams-Watters_, Aug 20 2013
mathematica: a[n_] := (DivisorSigma[0, n^2] - 1)/2 - DivisorSigma[0, n] + 1; Array[a, 104] (* _Robert G. Wilson v_, Dec 16 2009 *)
program: a089233 n = sum $ [a063524 $ gcd u v | let ds = tail $ a027750_row n,
u <- ds, v <- dropWhile (<= u) ds]
